text:
This probably sounds weird, but the "knees" you think are bent backward on a flamingo (or any bird for that matter) are actually their "heels."  Think about a chicken leg.  The thigh of the chicken isn't the "drumstick," but rather is the meat connected to its hip and the "drumstick" is the calf of the chicken.  A flamingo's legs are longer in proportion to a chicken's, but the bones and muscles are arranged the same way.  Also, think of a bird's feet as the same thing as a person's forefeet and toes.

Birds and a lot of other animals have hind feet and hind paws that are the same as our forefeet and toes, while their mid and hindfeet are very extended compared to ours.  If you walk on your toes you are walking in the same manner that most animals walk all the time.
